  <h1 id="top">Normal Distribution &amp; Central Limit Theorem</h1>
  <p>The normal is the backbone of Modules 1.7–1.8. Master standardization and the $\Phi$ table now. Then watch the CLT demo to see why averages from any distribution become Normal.</p>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 1: UNIFORM DISTRIBUTION ═══ -->
<h2 id="uniform">Theory — Uniform Distribution</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Uniform$(a,b)$ assigns equal density across an interval. Probability = length ratio — no integral needed.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Uniform(a, b) — PDF and CDF</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$f(x) = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;b-a&#125;, \quad F(x) = \frac&#123;x-a&#125;&#123;b-a&#125; \quad \text&#123;for&#125;\; a \le x \le b$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X] = (a+b)/2$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = (b-a)^2/12$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; Median $= (a+b)/2$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Probability = length ratio</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$P(c \le X \le d) = \frac&#123;d - c&#125;&#123;b - a&#125; \quad (a \le c \le d \le b)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Faster than integrating. Median condition: $(a+b)/2 = m$ gives parameter directly. (2025 Q19)</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 2: EXPONENTIAL DISTRIBUTION ═══ -->
<h2 id="exponential">Theory — Exponential Distribution</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Exponential$(\lambda)$ models waiting times. The tail $e^&#123;-\lambda x&#125;$ and memorylessness property answer most GATE problems in one line.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Exponential(λ) — PDF, tail, CDF</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$f(x) = \lambda e^&#123;-\lambda x&#125;, \quad P(X > x) = e^&#123;-\lambda x&#125;, \quad x \ge 0$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X] = 1/\lambda$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = 1/\lambda^2$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; Rate $\lambda$, mean $1/\lambda$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Memorylessness — the one-line shortcut</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$P(X > s + t \mid X > s) = P(X > t)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Past waiting time is forgotten. Only exponential (continuous) and geometric (discrete) have this.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">Rate $\lambda$ vs mean $1/\lambda$ — read the problem carefully</span>
    "Exponential with mean 4" → $\lambda = 1/4$. "Exponential with rate 0.5" → $\lambda = 0.5$. GATE sometimes states the mean directly (2026 Q34 says "mean $\lambda$" — that means rate $= 1/\lambda$). Plug the right value into $e^&#123;-\lambda x&#125;$.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 3: NORMAL + STANDARDIZATION ═══ -->
<h2 id="normal">Theory — Normal Distribution &amp; Standardization</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  The normal is symmetric, bell-shaped, and fully determined by $\mu$ and $\sigma^2$ (variance — not SD). All normal probabilities reduce to $\Phi(z)$ after one standardization step.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Normal(μ, σ²) — PDF</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$f(x) = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;\sigma\sqrt&#123;2\pi&#125;&#125;\, e^&#123;-(x-\mu)^2/(2\sigma^2)&#125;$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X]=\mu$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)=\sigma^2$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; Mean = Median = Mode = $\mu$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Standardization — convert any Normal to Z</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$Z = \frac&#123;X - \mu&#125;&#123;\sigma&#125; \sim N(0,1) \quad\Rightarrow\quad P\!\left(a \le X \le b\right) = \Phi\!\!\left(\frac&#123;b-\mu&#125;&#123;\sigma&#125;\right) - \Phi\!\!\left(\frac&#123;a-\mu&#125;&#123;\sigma&#125;\right)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Symmetry: $\Phi(-z) = 1 - \Phi(z)$. &nbsp; $\Phi(0) = 0.5$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Linear transform of Normal</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$aX + b \sim N(a\mu + b,\; a^2\sigma^2)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">The shift $b$ moves the mean only. The scale $a$ multiplies the mean and squares into the variance.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Sum of independent Normals</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$X_1 + X_2 \sim N(\mu_1+\mu_2,\; \sigma_1^2+\sigma_2^2)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Variances add — never add standard deviations. Requires independence. (2026 Q10)</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Φ key values grid -->
<div class="rule-card" style="margin-top:16px;">
  <div class="rule-card__label">Key $\Phi(z)$ values — memorise these</div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr);gap:6px;margin-top:10px;">
