<!-- ═══ VIZ 2: CLT DEMO ═══ -->
<h2 id="viz2">Interactive 2 — Central Limit Theorem Demo</h2>
<p style="color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;font-size:0.92rem;">
  Sample <strong>n</strong> values from any distribution. Compute the sample mean $\bar&#123;X&#125;$. Repeat. Watch the distribution of $\bar&#123;X&#125;$ converge to Normal — regardless of the source distribution.
</p>

<div class="gd-formula-panel gd-formula-panel--single">
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">CLT</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\bar&#123;X&#125;_n = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;n&#125;\sum_&#123;i=1&#125;^n X_i \xrightarrow&#123;d&#125; \mathcal&#123;N&#125;\!\left(\mu,\,\frac&#123;\sigma^2&#125;&#123;n&#125;\right) \text&#123; as &#125; n\to\infty$$</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Step 1: pick source distribution -->
<div class="gd-controls" style="margin-bottom:14px;">
  <div class="gd-controls__title">Step 1 — Source distribution (population to sample from)</div>
  <div class="clt-src-tabs" id="clt-src-tabs">
    <button class="clt-src-tab clt-src-tab--active" data-src="uniform">Uniform(0,1)</button>
    <button class="clt-src-tab" data-src="exponential">Exponential(1)</button>
    <button class="clt-src-tab" data-src="bernoulli">Bernoulli(0.3)</button>
    <button class="clt-src-tab" data-src="bimodal">Bimodal</button>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Source chart — shows the population shape -->
<div class="gd-chart">
  <div class="gd-chart__title" id="clt-src-title">Source distribution</div>
  <div id="clt-src-chart"></div>
</div>

<!-- Step 2: sample from it -->
<div class="gd-controls" style="margin-bottom:14px;">
  <div class="gd-controls__title">Step 2 — Draw samples and collect means</div>
  <div class="gd-control">
    <label class="gd-control__label"><span class="gd-control__sym">n</span> Sample size per draw</label>
    <span class="gd-control__value" id="clt-n-val">5</span>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-control--full">
    <input class="gd-control__slider" type="range" id="clt-n" min="1" max="50" step="1" value="5">
  </div>
</div>

<div style="display:flex;gap:10px;align-items:center;margin-bottom:12px;flex-wrap:wrap;">
  <button class="gd-btn gd-btn--primary" id="clt-sample-btn">Draw 1 sample</button>
  <button class="gd-btn gd-btn--secondary" id="clt-many-btn">Draw 500 more</button>
  <button class="gd-btn gd-btn--secondary" id="clt-reset-btn">Reset</button>
</div>

<div class="clt-sample-count" id="clt-count">0</div>
<div class="clt-sample-label">sample means collected</div>

<!-- Means chart — distribution of X̄ -->
<div class="gd-chart" style="margin-top:0;">
  <div class="gd-chart__title">Distribution of $\bar&#123;X&#125;$ (sample means) — watch it go Normal!</div>
  <div id="clt-means-chart"></div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insights__title">What CLT tells us</div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--active" id="clt-ins-1">Collect more samples — the histogram will approach a bell curve shape.</div>
  <div class="gd-insight" id="clt-ins-2">Std dev of X̄ = σ/√n (standard error). Larger n → narrower distribution.</div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn" id="clt-ins-3">Works regardless of source distribution shape!</div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ WORKED EXAMPLES ═══ -->
<h2 id="examples">Worked Examples</h2>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 1 · Uniform — probability, mean, variance</span>
    <p>$X \sim \text&#123;Uniform&#125;(2, 8)$. Find $P(3 \le X \le 5)$, $E[X]$, and $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Probability (length ratio):</strong> $P(3 \le X \le 5) = \frac&#123;5-3&#125;&#123;8-2&#125; = \frac&#123;2&#125;&#123;6&#125; = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;3&#125; \approx 0.333$.</p>
    <p><strong>Mean:</strong> $E[X] = (2+8)/2 = 5$.</p>
    <p><strong>Variance:</strong> $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = (8-2)^2/12 = 36/12 = 3$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Length ratio is always faster than integration for uniform. Median also equals 5 — the midpoint.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">P(3≤X≤5) = 1/3 · E[X] = 5 · Var(X) = 3</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 2 · GATE 2025 Q21 — Exponential rate from tail probability (MCQ)</span>
    <p>For $X \sim \text&#123;Exponential&#125;(\lambda)$, it is given that $P(X \ge 2) = 0.25$. Find $\lambda$.<br>
    (A) $\ln 2$ &nbsp;&nbsp; (B) $\ln 4$ &nbsp;&nbsp; (C) $\ln 3$ &nbsp;&nbsp; (D) $\ln 0.25$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Tail formula:</strong> $P(X \ge 2) = e^&#123;-2\lambda&#125; = 0.25 = 1/4$.</p>
    <p><strong>Solve:</strong> $-2\lambda = \ln(1/4) = -\ln 4$, so $\lambda = \frac&#123;\ln 4&#125;&#123;2&#125; = \ln(4^&#123;1/2&#125;) = \ln 2$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Trap: stopping at $2\lambda = \ln 4$ and picking (B). You must halve it. $\ln 4 / 2 = \ln\sqrt&#123;4&#125; = \ln 2$.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Answer: (A) λ = ln 2</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 3 · Normal — standardize and apply Φ</span>
    <p>Heights $X \sim N(\mu=170,\; \sigma^2=100)$ cm. Find $P(160 \le X \le 185)$.<br>
    Use $\Phi(1)=0.8413$, $\Phi(1.5)=0.9332$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Extract σ:</strong> $\sigma = \sqrt&#123;100&#125; = 10$ (second parameter is variance).</p>
    <p><strong>Standardize:</strong> $z_1 = \frac&#123;160-170&#125;&#123;10&#125; = -1$, &nbsp; $z_2 = \frac&#123;185-170&#125;&#123;10&#125; = 1.5$.</p>
    <p><strong>Compute:</strong> $P = \Phi(1.5) - \Phi(-1) = 0.9332 - (1 - 0.8413) = 0.9332 - 0.1587 = 0.7745$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Used symmetry $\Phi(-1) = 1 - \Phi(1)$ to avoid a negative-z lookup.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Answer: ≈ 0.7745</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 4 · GATE 2025 Q20 — Normal linear transform from moments (MCQ)</span>
    <p>$X = aZ + b$, $Z \sim N(0,1)$. Given $E[X]=1$, $E[(X-E[X])^2]=4$, $E[(X-E[X])Z]=-2$. Find $a$ and $b$.<br>
    (A) $a=-2, b=1$ &nbsp;&nbsp; (B) $a=2, b=-1$ &nbsp;&nbsp; (C) $a=-2, b=-1$ &nbsp;&nbsp; (D) $a=1, b=1$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Mean:</strong> $E[X] = aE[Z] + b = 0 + b = b = 1$. So $b = 1$.</p>
    <p><strong>Variance:</strong> $E[(X-E[X])^2] = \text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = a^2\text&#123;Var&#125;(Z) = a^2 \cdot 1 = a^2 = 4$. So $a = \pm 2$.</p>
    <p><strong>Cross-moment pins the sign:</strong> $E[(X-E[X])Z] = E[aZZ] = a\,E[Z^2] = a \cdot 1 = a = -2$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Variance gives $|a|=2$ but cannot fix sign. The cross-moment $E[(X-\mu)Z]=a$ provides the sign directly.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Answer: (A) a = −2, b = 1</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ GATE ANGLE ═══ -->
<div class="gd-gate-box">
  <div class="gd-gate-box__title">GATE DA Angle</div>
  <p><strong>Memorise $\Phi$ values:</strong> $\Phi(1)=0.841$, $\Phi(1.5)=0.933$, $\Phi(1.645)=0.95$, $\Phi(1.96)=0.975$, $\Phi(2)=0.977$, $\Phi(2.576)=0.995$. These numbers solve 80% of Normal MCQs.</p>
  <p><strong>$N(\mu, \sigma^2)$ trap:</strong> The second parameter is the <em>variance</em>. Take $\sigma=\sqrt&#123;\sigma^2&#125;$ before standardizing. $N(0,9)$ → $\sigma=3$, not 9. (2025 Q20)</p>
  <p><strong>Symmetry shortcut:</strong> $\Phi(-z) = 1 - \Phi(z)$. Negative-$z$ lookups become positive ones. $P(Z \le -1.5) = 1 - 0.933 = 0.067$.</p>
  <p><strong>Exponential: rate vs mean.</strong> "Exponential with mean $m$" means $\lambda = 1/m$. Plug $\lambda$ — not $m$ — into $e^&#123;-\lambda x&#125;$. Stopping at $2\lambda = \ln 4$ without halving is the (B) trap on 2025 Q21.</p>
  <p><strong>CLT standard error:</strong> "Sample of $n=36$ from $\mu=100$, $\sigma=12$" → $\text&#123;SE&#125; = 12/\sqrt&#123;36&#125; = 2$. Standardize $\bar&#123;X&#125;$: $Z = (\bar&#123;X&#125;-\mu)/\text&#123;SE&#125;$. Then look up $\Phi$. Appears yearly in hypothesis testing questions.</p>
  <p><strong>$\text&#123;Var&#125;(aX+b) = a^2\sigma^2$.</strong> The shift $b$ disappears from variance. For independent normals, variances add: $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X+Y) = \sigma_X^2 + \sigma_Y^2$ (never add SDs).</p>
</div>

